elements.content: We report herein a new cobalt­(II/III) mixed-valence metal–organic framework formulated as [CoIICo2 III(μ3-O)­(bdc)3(tpt)]·guest 1, where bdc = benzene-1,4-dicarboxylate and tpt = 2,4,6-tri­(4-pyridinyl)-1,3,5-triazine, which can be used as a redox-active heterogeneous catalyst for selective oxidation of cyclohexene on the allylic position without destroying the adjacent double bond. Two oxidants were chosen to demonstrate this result. For using tert-butyl hydroperoxide, the conversion rate is 63% and only allylic oxidation products (tert-butyl-2-cyclohexenyl-1-peroxide, 86%; 2-cyclohexen-1-one, 14%) are found, whereas if using O2 as oxidant, a total conversion of 38% is achieved and also only the allylic oxidation products (cyclohexenyl hydroperoxide, 72%; 2-cyclohexen-1-one, 20%; and cyclohex-2-en-1-ol, 8%) are found. The absence of any adduct on the double bond may be due to the unique radical chain mechanism triggered by the mixed-valent [CoIICo2 III(μ3-O)] centers.

elements.clean_text:
Introduction

The catalytic property of metal-organic frameworks (MOFs) draws a growing attention in recent years owing to the significant porosity, diversified ligand decoration, and variable coordination chemistry of metal ions. Peroxidation of cyclohexene, as one of the model reactions for selectively introducing peroxy bond into the allylic position (without breaking the adjacent and reductive double bond), was initially developed by Kharasch et al. in 1950s. After years of investigation, this reaction has been known to involve transition-metal centers, such as copper, manganese, and cobalt, for higher efficiency of catalytic activities. However, these reactions are homogeneous. To achieve larger scale synthesis, the development of heterogeneous catalyst is more desired.

elements.content: MOFs, constructed by metal-containing secondary building units (SBUs) and organic linkers, are designed for this purpose. The pioneering work using a cobalt­(II) MOF toward catalyzing cyclohexene oxidation was demonstrated by Volkmer et al., the best conversion is only 27.5% (for MFU-1). Moreover, due to the reductive nature of the double bond, many other oxidative products were also detected (), indicating low selectivity. Later on, Van Der Voort et al. found MIL-47, which contains one-dimensional O–VIV–O chain exhibiting a much higher conversion (up to 60%), but the metal leaches out during the reaction and diverts the reaction pathways. Thus, the selectivity is also low.

Enlightened by these studies, we assume that MOFs with redox-active metal centers are important to catalyze the oxidation reaction. In this context, the trigonal planar trimer [M3(μ3-O)­(RCOO)6], in which the metal ions exhibit flexible oxidation states, drew our attention, especially for M = Co. In contrast to its Cr, Fe, and Ni analogues, triangular [Co3(μ3-O/OH)] SBUs have only been found in a few MOFs, including [Co3(OH)­(pdc)3]·H2O (pdc = pyridine-3,5-dicarboxylate), [CoII 3(μ3-O)­(OH)­(cpt)3(H2O)2]·guest (Hcpt = 4-(4′-carboxyphenyl)-1,2,4-triazole), and MCF-18 series. In all of these MOFs, the [Co3(μ3-O/OH)] SBUs are in situ formed during the solvothermal reactions in the presence of carboxylates and N-heterocyclic ligands. Hence, we reason that the presence of both N-heterocyclic ligands and carboxylates in basic condition is critical to achieve the [CoIICo2 III(μ3-O)] SBUs.

Enlightened by these studies, we assume that MOFs with redox-active metal centers are important to catalyze the oxidation reaction. In this context, the trigonal planar trimer [M3(μ3-O)(RCOO)6], in which the metal ions exhibit flexible oxidation states, drew our attention, especially for M = Co. In contrast to its Cr, Fe, and Ni analogues, triangular [Co3(μ3-O/OH)] SBUs have only been found in a few MOFs, including [Co3(OH)(pdc)3]⋅H2O (pdc = pyridine-3,5-dicarboxylate), [CoII 3(μ3-O)(OH)(cpt)3(H2O)2]⋅guest (Hcpt = 4-(4'-carboxyphenyl)-1,2,4-triazole), and MCF-18 series. In all of these MOFs, the [Co3(μ3-O/OH)] SBUs are in situ formed during the solvothermal reactions in the presence of carboxylates and N-heterocyclic ligands. Hence, we reason that the presence of both N-heterocyclic ligands and carboxylates in basic condition is critical to achieve the [CoIICo2 III(μ3-O)] SBUs.

elements.content: To ensure the large porosity, the triangular N-heterocyclic ligand 2,4,6-tri­(4-pyridinyl)-1,3,5-triazine (tpt) and a long dicarboxylate ligand benzene-1,4-dicarboxylate (bdc) were chosen. After solvothermal treatment, we isolated a mixed-valence cobalt­(II/III)-based MOF, [CoIICo2 III(μ3-O)­(bdc)3(tpt)]·guest 1 (guest = 4DMF and 3H2O), with large porosity. Two oxidants were chosen to demonstrate the catalytic ability of 1 for oxidizing cyclohexene. Using tert-butyl hydroperoxide (TBHP) as an oxidant, the total conversion rate is 63%, whereas if using O2 as an oxidant, the total conversion rate is 38%. These conversion rates are better than many other reported MOFs to date (see below). More importantly, only the allylic oxidation products are detectable for both reactions, and the selectivity toward peroxide product is up to 86 and 72% for TBHP and O2, respectively. We postulate that such a high selectivity is due to the unique radical mechanism promoted by the mixed-valent Co3 unit.

elements.content: Compound 1 crystallizes in hexagonal space group P 63/ mmc . The planar triangular [CoIICo2 III(μ3-O)] SBU is extended by six dicarboxylates and three tpt ligands (a). Co atom shows a six-coordinate octahedral geometry consisting of four O atoms from bdc ligands (Co–O = 2.093 Å), one μ3-O2– (Co–O = 2.025 Å), and one N atom from tpt ligand (Co–N = 2.170 Å). Topologically, the tpt ligand is treated as three-connected node, whereas the [CoIICo2 III(μ3-O)] SBU can be considered as a nine-connected node. Thus, the three-dimensional (3D) framework of 1 exhibits a noninterpenetrating (3,9)-connected network with the point symbol {421·615}­{43}. The framework consists of two kinds of microporous cages, namely, cages A and B, with dimensionality of 12.9 × 12.9 × 7.6 and 10.9 × 10.9 × 15.3 Å3, respectively (b). For cage A, it is a cavity inside a dicapped trigonal antiprism formed by six [CoIICo2 III(μ3-O)] SBUs, two facing tpt ligands and six bdc ligands. Cages A are running along the c axis and are separated by the tpt ligands. For cage B, it is the cavity inside a trigonal bipyramid formed by five [CoIICo2 III(μ3-O)] SBUs and six bdc ligands. Each cage B is surrounded by six cages A and interconnected through the void space between ligands (c,d). The porous structure affords total void space of 58.8% crystallographic volume.

Results and Discussion

Compound 1 crystallizes in hexagonal space group  P 63/ mmc . The planar triangular [CoIICo2 III(μ3-O)] SBU is extended by six dicarboxylates and three tpt ligands (a). Co atom shows a six-coordinate octahedral geometry consisting of four O atoms from bdc ligands (Co-O = 2.093 Å), one μ3-O2- (Co-O = 2.025 Å), and one N atom from tpt ligand (Co-N = 2.170 Å). Topologically, the tpt ligand is treated as three-connected node, whereas the [CoIICo2 III(μ3-O)] SBU can be considered as a nine-connected node. Thus, the three-dimensional (3D) framework of 1 exhibits a noninterpenetrating (3,9)-connected network with the point symbol {421⋅615}{43}. The framework consists of two kinds of microporous cages, namely, cages A and B, with dimensionality of 12.9 × 12.9 × 7.6 and 10.9 × 10.9 × 15.3 Å3, respectively (b). For cage A, it is a cavity inside a dicapped trigonal antiprism formed by six [CoIICo2 III(μ3-O)] SBUs, two facing tpt ligands and six bdc ligands. Cages A are running along the c axis and are separated by the tpt ligands. For cage B, it is the cavity inside a trigonal bipyramid formed by five [CoIICo2 III(μ3-O)] SBUs and six bdc ligands. Each cage B is surrounded by six cages A and interconnected through the void space between ligands (c,d). The porous structure affords total void space of 58.8% crystallographic volume.

elements.content: X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy was used to reveal the valence state of the cobalt ions. As shown in a, the peaks with binding energies of 779.6 and 795.6 eV are attributed to 2p3/2 and 2p1/2 electrons of the CoIII ions. Meanwhile, the peaks at 781.2 and 796.9 eV belong to the 2p3/2 and 2p1/2 electrons of the CoII ions. Moreover, the peaks at 784.1 and 800.4 eV are attributed to the CoII satellites and the peaks at 803.0 and 786.8 eV are attributed to the CoIII satellites. All of these observations correspond to the presence of mixed-valence [CoIICoIII 2(μ3-O)] SBUs, in good agreement with the crystallographic result.

elements.content: To further confirm the presence of μ3-O2– rather than μ3-OH–, we perform the infrared (IR) measurement on the activated 1 (Figure S7). As we all know, the hydroxyl group has typical band at 3670–3580 cm–1 with strong intensity, which belongs to the O–H stretching vibrations. However, the band was not observed in our case. In addition, experimentally, μ3-O2– is usually planar coordinated with the metal ions but the μ3-OH– is often coordinated out of the plane. Thus, we can safely conclude that μ3-O2– is the bridging group in 1 rather than μ3-OH–.

elements.content: Also, the temperature-dependent direct-current (dc) susceptibility was measured to reveal the spin state of 1. As shown in b, the χM T product at room temperature is 9.66 cm3 K mol–1, higher than the spin-only value of one CoII ion and two high-spin CoIII ions (7.87 cm3 K mol–1 for g = 2.0), owing to the orbital contribution of CoII ions. Upon cooling, χM T decreases fast and finally reaches to 1.94 cm3 K mol–1 at 2 K, which is close to the value of a magnetically isolated CoII ion (1.73 cm3 K mol–1 for S eff = 1/2 with g = 4.3). In addition, the magnetization at 2.0 K increases rapidly in low field but slowly in high field, finally reaches 2.98 μB at 7 T. Fitting the data above 150 K with Curie–Weiss law gives C = 12.22 cm3 K mol–1 and θ = −74.96 K. The large negative value of Weiss constant results from strong antiferromagnetic interactions as well as the spin–orbit coupling of CoII ions.

Using S 1 = S 3 = S Co(III) = 2, S 2 = S Co(II) = 3/2 ion, and fixed g 1 = g 3 = 2.30, we obtained the best fit of J 1 = −6.68 cm–1, J 2 = −2.61 cm–1, and g 2 = 2.43 (b, inset). elements.content: Cyclic voltammetry (CV) measurement was performed to reveal the redox activity of the cobalt ions (d). The redox couple [CoIICoIII 2(μ3-O)]6+/[CoIII 3(μ3-O)]7+ was observed at E 1/2 = −825 mV vs Ag/Ag+, and the separation between the oxidation and the reduction peaks is 140 mV. Such a separation comes from slow electron transfer kinetics/low conductivity of the MOF materials. The quasi-reversibility of the redox process was confirmed by the calculated ratio of |i Pa/i Pc| ≈ 1, and the shapes of CV curves maintain after three cycles, indicating 1 is stable during the redox process. In addition, detailed electrochemical measurements give the molar ratio of CoII/CoIII = 1:1.7 (see Supporting Information for detail), which agrees with the presence of mixed-valence CoIICo2 IIISBUs.

elements.content: The N2 adsorption isothermal of 1 at 77 K shows a type-I microporous feature (c). The gas uptake increases sharply in low-pressure region and up to 206 cm3 g–1 (STP) at 0.22P/P 0, attributing to monolayer adsorption. Then, the N2 uptake increases slowly and finally reaches 256 cm3 g–1 at 1 bar. For the degasing process, no hysteresis was observed. Langmuir surface area is calculated to be 1008 m2 g–1. elements.content: Because compound 1 displays significant porosity as well as redox activity and stability, it may be a good heterogeneous catalyst for selectively oxidizing alkene. Thus, we chose cyclohexene as a model substrate to test this hypothesis. Two oxidants are chosen as representatives. The first one is the tert-butyl hydroperoxide (TBHP). After activation, equimolar reactants of cyclohexene and TBHP were mixed in the presence of 1 at 70 °C. The conversion rates were monitored in situ by gas chromatography–mass spectroscopy using 1,2,4-trichlorobenzene as internal standard. During the first 2 h (a), a 40% conversion was observed, which corresponds to a turnover frequency of 144 h–1 (based on Co3 SBU). In the following 22 h, a total 63% conversion was observed, corresponding to a turnover number 360.

The oxidation of cyclohexene under aerobic condition was also performed. Significantly, a conversion up to 37.9% after 24 h was observed, corresponding to a time-of-flight (TOF) 5.7 h–1 and a TON 137. Such a conversion rate is the highest in Co-based MOFs and only below the Fe-containing MOF MIL-101 (). Similar to the result of TBHP, the reaction under aerobic condition catalyzed by 1 gave allylic oxidation products only, showing high selectivity. Other double-bond broken products, such as d and e, in are not detected. Differently, another oxidative product c (with 8%) was observed. Though the selectivity of the main product a2 is reduced to 72% and the second product b increases to 20%, to the best of our knowledge, this is the highest selectivity toward peroxidation products under aerobic condition.

In the oxidation of cyclohexene, we reason that such a high performance is due to the unique feature of the [CoIICo2 III(μ3-O)] center for mediating the radical generation of chain reaction (). The TBHP molecule may first attack the mixed-valence [CoIICoIII 2(μ3-O)] SBU and coordinate with the CoII center. Subsequently, owing to the Haber–Weiss decomposition, the tert-butoxy radical and the hydroxyl radical are generated. Meanwhile, the resulting tert-butoxy radical exchanges hydrogen atom with one cyclohexene molecule and generates 3-cyclohexenyl radical and tert-butanol. Moreover, the hydroxyl radical reacts with one TBHP molecule to generate tert-butyl peroxy radical and water. Finally, the resulting tert-butyl peroxy reacts with the 3-cyclohexenyl radical to give the main product a1. Upon the leaving of tert-butyl peroxy and the formation of water, the catalyst recovers and the catalytic cycle is accomplished. If using O2 as an oxidant, similar mechanism can be proposed (Scheme S1). The [CoIICoIII 2(μ3-O)] is first attacked by O2 molecule and a charge transfer occurs. Subsequently, the cyclohexene reacts with the adduct to afford a 3-cyclohexenyl radical and a hydrogen peroxide radical, which simultaneously reacts to give cyclohexenyl hydroperoxide. Finally, with the leaving of hydrogen peroxide radical, the catalyst recovers.

elements.content: To reveal the heterogeneity of the reaction, a hot filtration experiment was conducted (Figure S2). After removal of the catalyst, the reaction almost ceased for both oxidants, indicating the heterogeneous nature of the catalyst. The inductively coupled plasma data of the reaction solution show that the reaction solution contains only trace amounts of Co ions (<0.5% Co leaching out), indicating that the catalyst did not decompose during the reaction. Moreover, the catalyst 1 can be recovered and continuously used for four runs, indicating a reasonably good recyclability and stability (b). After the first run, a ca. 15% reduction of conversion rate may be caused by the partially blocking of the active site by the organic substance. In the following runs, the conversion remains nearly constant. The recovered catalyst was tested by powder X-ray diffraction (PXRD) (Figure S6), revealing the structural completeness of the catalyst. The X-ray photoelectron spectrum of recovered catalyst of 1 still reveals a mixed-valence cobalt­(II,III) state (Figure S8).

elements.content: To further confirm the catalytic activity of 1, another cyclic alkene derivative cyclooctene was chosen for the oxidation using TBHP (). After 24 h, 32% conversion of cyclooctene was observed, which is corresponding to TON 115.2 and TOF 4.8 h–1, and smaller than those of cyclohexene. The lower conversion may be caused by the fact that the mass transfer and the reactant diffusion inside the pore would be more difficult, further indicating the reaction happens inside the pore. The product detection indicates that the major component is the epoxide d3 with selectivity of 73% (Figures S3 and S4), and the allylic oxidation products are a3 and b3 only with selectivities of 20 and 7%, respectively. The reason for the selectivity toward epoxide rather than the allylic oxidation products has been illuminated in the literature, namely, the conformation effect; almost orthogonal allylic C–H bonds make the allylic functionalization more difficult than for cyclohexene and lead to the formation of epoxide. And the observation is in agreement with the previous reports.

elements.content: In summary, we demonstrated that a MOF material with redox-active [CoIICo2 III(μ3-O)] center exhibits high catalytic activity and selectivity toward the oxidation of cyclohexene. Specifically, the oxidation reaction can be efficiently promoted by 1, to a conversion rate of 63 and 38% for TBHP and O2, respectively. Moreover, selectivities toward peroxide are high, up to 86 and 72% for TBHP and O2, respectively. The absence of the double-bond oxidative products presumably indicates a radical mechanism, whereas the lower conversion rate for the larger cyclooctene indicates the steric effect of the channels.
elements.clean_text:
Conclusions

In summary, we demonstrated that a MOF material with redox-active [CoIICo2 III(μ3-O)] center exhibits high catalytic activity and selectivity toward the oxidation of cyclohexene. Specifically, the oxidation reaction can be efficiently promoted by 1, to a conversion rate of 63 and 38% for TBHP and O2, respectively. Moreover, selectivities toward peroxide are high, up to 86 and 72% for TBHP and O2, respectively. The absence of the double-bond oxidative products presumably indicates a radical mechanism, whereas the lower conversion rate for the larger cyclooctene indicates the steric effect of the channels.

cln_elements.content:
Compound 1 crystallizes in hexagonal space group P 63/ mmc . The planar triangular [CoIICo2 III(μ3-O)] SBU is extended by six dicarboxylates and three tpt ligands (a). Co atom shows a six-coordinate octahedral geometry consisting of four O atoms from bdc ligands (Co–O = 2.093 Å), one μ3-O2– (Co–O = 2.025 Å), and one N atom from tpt ligand (Co–N = 2.170 Å). Topologically, the tpt ligand is treated as three-connected node, whereas the [CoIICo2 III(μ3-O)] SBU can be considered as a nine-connected node. Thus, the three-dimensional (3D) framework of 1 exhibits a noninterpenetrating (3,9)-connected network with the point symbol {421·615}­{43}. The framework consists of two kinds of microporous cages, namely, cages A and B, with dimensionality of 12.9 × 12.9 × 7.6 and 10.9 × 10.9 × 15.3 Å3, respectively (b). For cage A, it is a cavity inside a dicapped trigonal antiprism formed by six [CoIICo2 III(μ3-O)] SBUs, two facing tpt ligands and six bdc ligands. Cages A are running along the c axis and are separated by the tpt ligands. For cage B, it is the cavity inside a trigonal bipyramid formed by five [CoIICo2 III(μ3-O)] SBUs and six bdc ligands. Each cage B is surrounded by six cages A and interconnected through the void space between ligands (c,d). The porous structure affords total void space of 58.8% crystallographic volume.

Also, the temperature-dependent direct-current (dc) susceptibility was measured to reveal the spin state of 1. As shown in b, the χM T product at room temperature is 9.66 cm3 K mol–1, higher than the spin-only value of one CoII ion and two high-spin CoIII ions (7.87 cm3 K mol–1 for g = 2.0), owing to the orbital contribution of CoII ions. Upon cooling, χM T decreases fast and finally reaches to 1.94 cm3 K mol–1 at 2 K, which is close to the value of a magnetically isolated CoII ion (1.73 cm3 K mol–1 for S eff = 1/2 with g = 4.3). In addition, the magnetization at 2.0 K increases rapidly in low field but slowly in high field, finally reaches 2.98 μB at 7 T. Fitting the data above 150 K with Curie–Weiss law gives C = 12.22 cm3 K mol–1 and θ = −74.96 K. The large negative value of Weiss constant results from strong antiferromagnetic interactions as well as the spin–orbit coupling of CoII ions.

The N2 adsorption isothermal of 1 at 77 K shows a type-I microporous feature (c). The gas uptake increases sharply in low-pressure region and up to 206 cm3 g–1 (STP) at 0.22P/P 0, attributing to monolayer adsorption. Then, the N2 uptake increases slowly and finally reaches 256 cm3 g–1 at 1 bar. For the degasing process, no hysteresis was observed. Langmuir surface area is calculated to be 1008 m2 g–1. Furthermore, the pore size distribution was calculated by dV/dW plot (c, inset), and two maximum values appear at 0.58 and 0.70 nm, corresponding to cages A and B, respectively.

Other than the active redox metal centers, the porosity of 1 may also serve as an important support for both reactions because catalysts with limited porosity often exhibit moderate catalytic activities. The pore size distribution gives two kinds of pore with diameters of 0.58 and 0.70 nm, both of which are large enough for the free diffusion of the reactants. To further confirm the free diffusion, the evacuated phase of 1 was soaked into the cyclohexene and TBHP for 24 h and subsequently tested by thermogravimetric analysis (TGA) (Figure S5). The TGA curves show 30.4% loading of cyclohexene and 33.1% loading of TBHP, confirming the free diffusion of reactant into the pore of 1. Furthermore, element analyses together with TGA indicate the capacities of 1 toward cyclohexene and TBHP are 5.2 and 5.5 per formula, respectively.
